<subSubSection id="C30F32F2DF03FFFD1EBE8A102FE0FC55" pageId="4" pageNumber="1409" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BAA6179DF03FFFD1EBE8A102F44FDBF" blockId="4.[211,319,559,582]" box="[211,319,559,582]" pageId="4" pageNumber="1409">
<emphasis id="B961BD6BDF03FFFD1EBE8A102F44FDBF" box="[211,319,559,582]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="1409">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BAA6179DF03FFFD1EBE8A692DB9FCF4" blockId="4.[211,1172,598,940]" pageId="4" pageNumber="1409">
The genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C151AFADF03FFFD1F278A692F97FD97" authorityName="Lacordaire" authorityYear="1848" box="[330,492,598,622]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Aetheomorpha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="1409" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B961BD6BDF03FFFD1F278A692F97FD97" box="[330,492,598,622]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="1409">Aetheomorpha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be recognized by the following characters: body cylindrical or suboval; head small, very short, smooth, perpendicular; mandibles very short; eyes small; antennae more or less robust, second and third antennomeres short and subconical, following antennomeres triangular; pronotum variable; scutellum large; elytra more or less lobed at sides; legs feeble, tarsi short, first tarsomere longer than second, third small, fourth slender; pygidium more or less exposed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BAA6179DF03FFFD1E938B2A2FE0FC55" blockId="4.[211,1172,598,940]" pageId="4" pageNumber="1409">
This genus is very closely allied to the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C151AFADF03FFFD1D7D8B2A2DEEFCD4" box="[784,917,789,813]" class="Ulvophyceae" family="Borodinellaceae" genus="Smaragdina" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ulotrichales" pageId="4" pageNumber="1409" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B961BD6BDF03FFFD1D7D8B2A2DEEFCD4" box="[784,917,789,813]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="1409">Smaragdina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but is usually distinguished by the following characters: antennae more robust; elytra with more or less distinct epipleural lobes; tarsi short; pygidium exposed. According to 
<bibRefCitation id="EF841C88DF03FFFD1D9D8B6A2AF4FC94" author="Jacoby M" box="[1008,1167,853,877]" pageId="4" pageNumber="1409" refId="ref12817" refString="Jacoby M. 1908. The fauna of British India, including Ceylon and Burma. Coleoptera, Chrysomelidae. Vol. 1. London: Taylor &amp; Francis, xx + 534 pp., 2 pls." type="book" year="1908">Jacoby (1908)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C151AFADF03FFFD1EBE8B4A2F0EFC74" authorityName="Lacordaire" authorityYear="1848" box="[211,373,885,909]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Aetheomorpha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="1409" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B961BD6BDF03FFFD1EBE8B4A2F0EFC74" box="[211,373,885,909]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="1409">Aetheomorpha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was not well defined as a genus-level taxon and is most possibly a transitional form.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
